    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "### Why does the trajectory stall at ~31°?\n\nThe phase portrait shows the pendulum spiralling toward an equilibrium around $\\theta \\approx 31°$, not reaching upright ($\\theta = 0$). This is a **torque saturation** effect.\n\nThe learned weights are large ($|\\mathbf{w}| \\approx 15$) but the torque clips at $u_{\\max} = 5\\,\\text{Nm}$, so the controller is pinned at maximum torque for most of the trajectory. The equilibrium is where that constant torque balances gravity:\n\n$$u_{\\max} = mgl\\sin\\theta \\quad\\Rightarrow\\quad \\theta^* = \\arcsin\\!\\left(\\frac{u_{\\max}}{mgl}\\right) = \\arcsin\\!\\left(\\frac{5}{9.81}\\right) \\approx 30.6°$$\n\nWith $u_{\\max} = 5$ and $mgl = 9.81$, the motor simply **cannot hold the pendulum upright** — it would need $u_{\\max} \\geq 9.81$ just to balance at the top. The CEM correctly found the best achievable policy: swing as high as the motor allows, then park at the highest sustainable angle.\n\nTo achieve a full swing-up we need to increase the torque limit.",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "## 5. Increasing the Torque Limit\n\nWith $u_{\\max} = 12\\,\\text{Nm}$ the motor can now statically hold the pendulum at any angle ($12 > mgl = 9.81$). Re-run CEM with the same policy structure.",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "/* Increase torque limit and re-run CEM */\nu_max : 12.0$\nnp_seed(42)$\n\n[best_w2, cost_history2] : np_cem(cem_cost, 3,\n  n_samples=40, n_elites=8, n_gens=25, sigma0=5.0, sigma_min=0.3)$\n\ncem_mu2 : np_to_list(best_w2)$\nprint(\"Higher-torque policy: w =\",\n  map(lambda([x], float(round(x * 100) / 100)), cem_mu2))$\nprint(\"Final cost:\", last(np_to_list(cost_history2)))$",
      "metadata": {},
      "execution_count": 66,
